# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: archaeological-institute-of-america
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/american-journal-of-archaeology] The journal primarily features articles about the art and archaeology of Europe and the Mediterranean world, including the Ancient Near East and Ancient Egypt, from Prehistoric to Late Antique times.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/american-journal-of-archaeology] It also publishes book reviews, museum exhibition reviews, and necrologies.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/american-journal-of-archaeology] It is published in January, April, July, and October each year in print and electronic editions.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/american-journal-of-archaeology] The publication was co-founded in 1885 by Princeton University professors Arthur Frothingham and Allan Marquand.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/american-journal-of-archaeology] Frothingham became its first editor-in-chief, serving until 1896.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/american-journal-of-archaeology] From 1940 to 1950, the journal published articles by Michael Ventris, Alice Kober, and Emmett Bennett, which contributed to the decipherment of the ancient Linear B script.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/american-journal-of-archaeology] The journal is published by University of Chicago Press on behalf of the Archaeological Institute of America, and its current editor-in-chief is Jane B.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/american-journal-of-archaeology] The journal's first woman editor-in-chief was Mary Hamilton Swindler.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/andrew-m-t-moore] Andrew Moore was born in Devon, England.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/andrew-m-t-moore] He read Modern History at the University of Oxford and in 1966 he joined Kathleen Kenyon's excavation in Jerusalem.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/andrew-m-t-moore] From 1967 to 1969, he did postgraduate studies at the University of London under John Evans.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/andrew-m-t-moore] He then undertook postgraduate research at the University of Oxford.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/andrew-m-t-moore] He completed his Doctor of Philosophy (DPhil) degree in 1978 with a doctoral thesis entitled *The Neolithic of the Levant*.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/andrew-m-t-moore] His supervisor was Dame Kathleen Kenyon.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/andrew-m-t-moore] He is currently director of the Abu Hureyra site and current president of the Archaeological Institute of America.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/andrew-m-t-moore] From 2000 to 2007, Moore served as the Dean of the College of Liberal Arts at Rochester Institute of Technology (RIT).
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/andrew-m-t-moore] Since 2007 he has been Dean of Graduate Studies at RIT.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/andrew-m-t-moore] In 2020, he joined the Comet Research Group and collaborated with them on research that reported high concentrations of iridium, platinum, nickel, and cobalt at the Younger Dryas boundary in material from Abu Hureyra.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/andrew-m-t-moore] They concluded that the evidence supports the Younger Dryas impact hypothesis, which has been comprehensively refuted by experts in archaeology, astronomy, and impact science.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] The **Archaeological Institute of America** (**AIA**) is North America's oldest learned society and largest organization devoted to the world of archaeology.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] AIA professionals have carried out archaeological fieldwork around the world and AIA has established research centers and schools in seven countries.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] As of 2019, the society had more than 6,100 members and more than 100 affiliated local societies in the United States and overseas.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] AIA members include professional archaeologists and members of the public.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] The AIA has established many archaeological organizations and protected many historical sites in the world.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] The AIA has hosted an annual meeting every year for over 120 years, where archaeologists present their latest work.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] The institute also has established scholarships for students and awarded archaeologists for their contributions to archaeology.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] The institute publishes a scholarly journal, the *American Journal of Archaeology* (*AJA*) and the magazine *Archaeology*.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] It is organized as a 501(c)(3) Public Charity; in 2024 it claimed total revenue of $6,452,285 and total assets of $18,603,495.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] The institute was founded in Boston in 1879 by Charles Eliot Norton with his colleagues and friends.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] They formed the society "for furthering and directing the archaeological and artistic investigation and research".
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] The institute subsequently expanded its reach through the establishment of schools of archaeology around the Mediterranean and in the southwestern United States.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] The *American Journal of Archaeology* (*AJA*) is the AIA's peer-reviewed academic journal, and *Archaeology* is the popular magazine issued by the institute.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] The *American Journal of Archaeology* was founded in 1885; the second series began in 1897.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] The AJA is published four times a year by the Archaeological Institute of America and the University of Chicago Press.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] The chief editors of the magazine are Emma Blake of the University of Arizona and Robert Schon of the University of Arizona.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] The journal presents original studies of the various peoples and material cultures of the Mediterranean and related regions, including North Africa (Egypt and Sudan), Western Asia (Caucasus), and Europe, from prehistory to late antiquity and beyond.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] The AJA encourages work that explores the cultures of the ancient Mediterranean along with other regions and periods and discusses the reasons for their continuing significance in the present.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] Also addressed in the journal are the history of the discipline, archaeological methodologies, and theoretical approaches.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] The Archaeological Institute of America has continuously published *Archaeology* since 1948.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] The magazine engages and entertains readers through vivid stories, surprising narratives, and inspiring images, bringing people of the past into our lives in the present.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] The magazine and website of the American Institute of Archaeology contain news of recent archaeological discoveries.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] The magazine is available at newsstands or on the website.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] The institute is governed by the council.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] All representatives must be AIA members who know AIA rules, work throughout the year and vote on issues, and attend meetings.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] The Governing Board prepares and approves the organization's annual budget and oversees its investments and donations, also conducting fundraising activities.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] The board meets three times a year and consists of seven officers elected by the council and twenty-four to thirty governors.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] There are three types of trustees, representing different constituents of AIA: General Trustees, Academic Trustees, and Society Trustees.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] The executive committee of the governing board holds at least three meetings annually.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] Greene is the current president (term 2023 to 2026), and Brian I.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] Daniels is the first vice president (term 2023 to 2026).
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] The AIA offers scholarships for young academic members and funds several students for excavation, research, publication, and site preservation.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] Its numerous awards recognize archaeologists and individuals and communities who have made outstanding contributions to the field and heritage conservation.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] As tourism and archaeology become more closely linked, archaeologists and site managers must consider the behavior and needs of visitors when deciding how to preserve and present sites.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] This requires consideration of issues such as how tourism will affect archaeological sites and impact research.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] In 2009, The Archaeological Institute of America partnered with the Adventure Travel Trade Association (ATTA) to develop a set of guidelines for people interested in organizing trips to archaeological sites.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] International Archaeology Day has been celebrated annually on the third Saturday of October by the AIA and is held throughout the month.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] This archaeological activity is suitable for all ages and interests.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] The event features archaeologist's lectures, tours of archaeological sites, and archaeological fairs.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] IAD Scavenger Hunt is an online Scavenger Hunt game published by AIA, and the ArchaeoDoodles Contest is a doodle event held by AIA in which participants create illustrations and graphics using 15 words or phrases recommended by AIA to help update AIA's list of terms and definitions.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] Holton Book Award, also known as the Holton Award, has been awarded annually to "a writer who, through a major work of non-fiction, represents the importance and excitement of archaeology to the general public".
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] It is named after journalist and writer Felicia A.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] Holton, who co-wrote *Koster: Americans in Search of Their Prehistoric Past* with archaeologist Stuart Struever in 1979.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeological-institute-of-america] In 2020 it was won by Australian historian and writer Billy Griffiths, for his 2018 work *Deep Time Dreaming: Uncovering Ancient Australia*, and in 2014 by British archaeologist Joyce Tyldesley for *Tutankhamen's Curse* (*Tutankhamen* in the US).
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Archaeologists study human prehistory and history, from the development of the first stone tools at Lomekwi in East Africa 3.3 million years ago up until recent decades.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Archaeology is distinct from palaeontology, which is the study of fossil remains.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Archaeology is particularly important for learning about prehistoric societies, for which, by definition, there are no written records.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Prehistory includes over 99% of the human past, from the Paleolithic until the advent of literacy in societies around the world.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Archaeology has various goals, ranging from understanding culture history to reconstructing past lifeways to documenting and explaining changes in human societies over time.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Derived from Greek, the term *archaeology* means "the study of ancient history".
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Archaeology developed out of antiquarianism in Europe during the 19th century and has since become a discipline practiced worldwide.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Nation-states have used archaeology to create particular visions of the past.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Since its early development, various specific sub-disciplines of archaeology have developed, including maritime archaeology, feminist archaeology, and archaeoastronomy, and numerous different scientific techniques have been developed to aid archaeological investigation.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Nonetheless, today, archaeologists face many problems, such as dealing with pseudoarchaeology, the looting of artifacts, a lack of public interest, and opposition to the excavation of human remains.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] In Ancient Mesopotamia, a foundation deposit of the Akkadian Empire ruler Naram-Sin (ruled c.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] 2200 BC) was discovered and analysed by king Nabonidus, c.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] 550 BC, who is thus known as the first archaeologist.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] He was also the first to date an archaeological artifact in his attempt to date Naram-Sin's temple during his search for it.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Even though his estimate was inaccurate by about 1,500 years, it was still a very good one considering the lack of accurate dating technology at the time.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] The science of archaeology (from Greek ἀρχαιολογία *archaiologia*, from ἀρχαῖος, *arkhaios* 'ancient' and -λογία, *-logia* 'study') grew out of the older multi-disciplinary study known as antiquarianism.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Antiquarians studied history with particular attention to ancient artifacts, manuscripts, and historical sites.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Antiquarianism focused on the empirical evidence available for understanding the past, encapsulated in the motto of the 18th century antiquary Richard Colt Hoare: "We speak from facts, not theory".
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Tentative steps towards the systematization of archaeology as a science took place during the Enlightenment period in Europe in the 17th and 18th centuries.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] In Imperial China during the Song dynasty (960–1279), figures such as Ouyang Xiu and Zhao Mingcheng established the tradition of Chinese epigraphy by investigating, preserving, and analyzing ancient Chinese bronze inscriptions from the Shang and Zhou periods.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Such antiquarian pursuits waned after the Song period, were revived in the 17th century during the Qing dynasty, but were always considered a branch of Chinese historiography rather than a separate discipline of archaeology.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] In Renaissance Europe, philosophical interest in the remains of Greco-Roman civilization and the rediscovery of classical culture began in the late Middle Ages, with humanism.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Cyriacus of Ancona was a restlessly itinerant Italian humanist and antiquarian who came from a prominent family of merchants in Ancona, a maritime republic on the Adriatic.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] He noted down his archaeological discoveries in his diary, *Commentaria* (in six volumes).
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Flavio Biondo, an Italian Renaissance humanist historian, created a systematic guide to the ruins and topography of ancient Rome in the early 15th century, for which he has been called an early founder of archaeology.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Antiquarians of the 16th century, including John Leland and William Camden, conducted surveys of the English countryside, drawing, describing and interpreting the monuments that they encountered.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] The *Oxford English Dictionary* first cites "archaeologist" in 1824; this soon became the usual term for one major branch of antiquarian activity.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] "Archaeology", from 1607 onward, initially meant what we would call "ancient history" generally, with the narrower modern sense first seen in 1837.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Twelfth-century Indian scholar Kalhana's writings involved recording local traditions and examining manuscripts, inscriptions, coins, and architecture, which are described as among the earliest traces of archaeology.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] One of his notable works is called *Rajatarangini*, which was completed c.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] 1150 and is considered one of the first historical works of India.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Among the first sites to undergo archaeological excavation were Stonehenge and other megalithic monuments in England.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] John Aubrey (1626–1697) was a pioneer archaeologist who recorded numerous megalithic and other field monuments in southern England.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] He was also ahead of his time in analysing his findings.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] He attempted to chart the chronological stylistic evolution of handwriting, medieval architecture, costume, and shield-shapes.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Excavations were also carried out by the Spanish military engineer Roque Joaquín de Alcubierre in the ancient towns of Pompeii and Herculaneum, both of which had been covered by ash during the Eruption of Mount Vesuvius in AD 79.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] These excavations began in 1748 in Pompeii and in 1738 in Herculaneum.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] The discovery of entire towns, complete with utensils and even human shapes, as well as the unearthing of frescos, had a big impact throughout Europe.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] However, before the development of modern techniques, excavations tended to be haphazard; the importance of concepts such as stratification and context was overlooked.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] In the mid-18th century, the German Johann Joachim Winckelmann lived in Rome and devoted himself to the study of Roman antiquities, gradually acquiring an unrivalled knowledge of ancient art.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Then, he visited the archaeological excavations being conducted at Pompeii and Herculaneum.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] He was one of the founders of scientific archaeology and first applied the categories of style on a large, systematic basis to the history of art.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] He was one of the first to separate Greek art into periods and time classifications.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Winckelmann has been called both "The prophet and founding hero of modern archaeology" and the father of the discipline of art history.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] The father of archaeological excavation was William Cunnington (1754–1810).
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] He undertook excavations in Wiltshire from around 1798, funded by Sir Richard Colt Hoare.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Cunnington made meticulous recordings of Neolithic and Bronze Age barrows, and the terms he used to categorize and describe them are still used by archaeologists today.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] President Thomas Jefferson also did his own excavations in 1784 using the trench method, on several Native American burial mounds in Virginia.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] His excavations were prompted by the "Moundbuilders" question; however, his careful methods led him to conclude that there was no reason why the ancestors of the Native Americans of his time could not have raised those mounds.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] One of the major achievements of 19th-century archaeology was the development of stratigraphy.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] The idea of overlapping strata tracing back to successive periods was borrowed from the new geological and palaeontological work of scholars like William Smith, James Hutton, and Charles Lyell.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] The systematic application of stratigraphy to archaeology first occurred during excavations of prehistorical and Bronze Age sites.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] In the third and fourth decades of the 19th century, archaeologists such as Jacques Boucher de Perthes and Christian Jürgensen Thomsen began to arrange the artifacts they had found in chronological order.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] A major figure in the development of archaeology into a rigorous science was army officer and ethnologist Augustus Pitt Rivers, who began excavations on his land in England in the 1880s.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Highly methodical by the standards of the time, he is widely regarded as the first scientific archaeologist.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] He arranged his artifacts by type or "Typology (archaeology)", and within types chronologically.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] This style of arrangement, designed to highlight evolutionary trends in human artifacts, was of enormous significance for accurately dating the objects.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] His most important methodological innovation was his insistence that *all* artifacts, not just beautiful or unique ones, be collected and catalogued.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] William Flinders Petrie is another man who may legitimately be called the Father of Archaeology.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Petrie was the first to scientifically investigate the Great Pyramid in Egypt during the 1880s.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] He was also responsible for mentoring and training a whole generation of Egyptologists, including Howard Carter who went on to achieve fame with the discovery of the tomb of 14th-century BC pharaoh Tutankhamun.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] The first stratigraphic excavation to gain wide public popularity was that of Hissarlik, on the site of ancient Troy, carried out by Heinrich Schliemann, Frank Calvert, and Wilhelm Dörpfeld in the 1870s.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] These scholars individuated nine different cities that had overlapped with one another, from prehistory to the Hellenistic period.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Meanwhile, the work of Sir Arthur Evans at Knossos in Crete revealed the ancient existence of an equally advanced Minoan civilization.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] The next major figure in the development of archaeology was Sir Mortimer Wheeler, whose highly disciplined approach to excavation and systematic coverage in the 1920s and 1930s brought the science on swiftly.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Wheeler developed the grid system of excavation, which was further improved by his student Kathleen Kenyon.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Archaeology became a professional activity in the first half of the 20th century, and it became possible to study archaeology as a subject in universities and even schools.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] By the end of the 20th century, nearly all professional archaeologists, at least in developed countries, were graduates.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Further adaptation and innovation in archaeology continued in this period, when maritime archaeology and urban archaeology became more prevalent, and rescue archaeology was developed in response to increasing commercial development.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] The purpose of archaeology is to learn more about past societies and the development of the human race.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Over 99% of human development has occurred within prehistoric cultures, which did not use writing; no written records exist for study.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Without such written sources, the only way to understand prehistoric societies is through archaeology.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Because archaeology is the study of past human activity, it stretches back to about 2.5 million years ago when the first stone tools were found – The Oldowan Industry.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Many important developments in human history occurred during prehistory, such as the evolution of humanity during the Paleolithic period, when the hominins developed from the australopithecines in Africa and eventually into modern *Homo sapiens*.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Archaeology also sheds light on many of humanity's technological advances, for instance, the ability to use fire, the development of stone tools, the discovery of metallurgy, the beginnings of religion, and the creation of agriculture.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Without archaeology, little or nothing would be known about humanity's use of material culture that predates writing.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] However, it is not only prehistoric, pre-literate cultures that can be studied using archaeology; historic, literate cultures can also be studied through the sub-discipline of historical archaeology.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] For many literate cultures, such as Ancient Greece and Mesopotamia, their surviving records are often incomplete and biased to some extent.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] In many societies, literacy was restricted to the elite classes, such as the clergy or the bureaucracy of the court or the temple.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] The literacy of aristocrats has sometimes been restricted to deeds and contracts.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] The interests and worldview of elites are often quite different from those of the populace.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Writings that were produced by people more representative of the general population were unlikely to find their way into libraries and be preserved there for posterity.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Thus, written records tend to reflect the biases, assumptions, cultural values, and possibly deceptions of a limited range of individuals, usually a small fraction of the larger population.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Hence, written records cannot be trusted as a sole source.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] The material record may be closer to a fair representation of society, though it is subject to its own biases, such as sampling bias and differential preservation.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Often, archaeology provides the only means of learning about the existence and behavior of people in the past.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Over the millennia, many thousands of cultures and societies, and billions of people, have come and gone, with little or no written record, or with existing records that are misrepresentative or incomplete.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Writing, as it is known today, did not exist in human civilization until the 4th millennium BC, and even then, only in a relatively small number of technologically advanced civilizations.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] In contrast, *Homo sapiens* has existed for at least 200,000 years, and other *Homo* species for millions of years (see Human evolution).
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] These civilizations are, not coincidentally, the best known; they have been open to historical inquiry for centuries, whereas the study of prehistoric cultures has only recently emerged.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Within a literate civilization, many events and important human practices may not be officially recorded.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Any knowledge of the early years of human civilization – the development of agriculture, cult practices of folk religion, the rise of the first cities – must come from archaeology.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] In addition to their scientific importance, archaeological remains sometimes have political or cultural significance for the descendants of the people who produced them, monetary value for collectors, or strong aesthetic appeal.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Many people identify archaeology with the recovery of such aesthetic, religious, political, or economic treasures rather than with the reconstruction of past societies.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] This view is often espoused in works of popular fiction, such as Raiders of the Lost Ark, The Mummy, and King Solomon's Mines.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] When unrealistic subjects are treated more seriously, accusations of pseudoscience are invariably levelled at their proponents *(see Pseudoarchaeology)*.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] However, these endeavours, real and fictional, are not representative of modern archaeology.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] There is no single approach to archaeological theory adopted by all archaeologists.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] In the 1960s, an archaeological movement largely led by American archaeologists like Lewis Binford and Kent Flannery arose that rebelled against the established cultural-history archaeology.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] They proposed a "New Archaeology", which would be more "scientific" and "anthropological", with hypothesis testing and the scientific method very important parts of what became known as processual archaeology.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] In the 1980s, a new postmodern movement arose led by the British archaeologists Michael Shanks, Christopher Tilley, Daniel Miller, and Ian Hodder, which has become known as post-processual archaeology.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] It questioned processualism's appeals to scientific positivism and impartiality; it emphasized the importance of a more self-critical theoretical reflexivity.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] However, processualists have criticized this approach as lacking scientific rigour.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] The validity of both processualism and post-processualism is still under debate.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Meanwhile, another theory, known as historical processualism, has emerged seeking to incorporate a focus on process and post-processual archaeology's emphasis on reflexivity and history.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] An archaeological investigation usually involves several distinct phases, each employing a variety of methods.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Before any practical work can begin, however, a clear objective for what the archaeologists are seeking to achieve must be agreed upon.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] This done, a site is surveyed to learn as much as possible about it and its surroundings.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Second, an excavation may be conducted to uncover any buried archaeological features.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] And third, the information collected during the excavation is studied and evaluated to achieve the archaeologists' original research objectives.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] It is then considered good practice for the information to be published so that it is available to other archaeologists and historians, although this is sometimes neglected.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Before actually starting to dig at a location, remote sensing can be used to identify where sites are located within a large area or to provide more information about sites or regions.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] There are two types of remote sensing instruments—passive and active.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Passive instruments detect natural energy reflected or emitted by the observed scene.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Passive instruments sense only radiation emitted by the object being viewed or reflected by the object from a source other than the instrument.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Active instruments emit energy and record the reflections.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Satellite imagery is an example of passive remote sensing.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] The distance to the object is determined by recording the time between the transmitted and backscattered pulses and using the speed of light to calculate the distance travelled.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Lidars can determine atmospheric profiles of aerosols, clouds, and other atmospheric constituents.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] The archaeological project then continues (or begins) with a field survey.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] A regional survey is an attempt to locate previously unknown sites within a region systematically.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] A site survey is an attempt to systematically locate features of interest, such as houses and middens, within a site.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Each of these two goals may be accomplished with largely the same methods.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Surveys were not widely practised in the early days of archaeology.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Cultural historians and earlier researchers were usually content to discover the locations of monumental sites from the local populace and to excavate only the plainly visible features there.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Gordon Willey pioneered the technique of regional settlement pattern survey in 1949 in the Viru Valley of coastal Peru, and survey of all levels became prominent with the rise of processual archaeology some years later.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Survey work has many benefits if performed as a preliminary exercise to, or even in place of, excavation.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] It requires relatively little time and expense because it does not involve processing large volumes of soil to search for artifacts.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] (Nevertheless, surveying a large region or site can be expensive, so archaeologists often employ sampling methods.) As with other forms of non-destructive archaeology, survey avoids ethical issues (of particular concern to descendant peoples) associated with destroying a site through excavation.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] It is the only way to gather some forms of information, such as settlement patterns and settlement structure.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Survey data are commonly assembled into maps, which may show surface features and/or artifact distribution.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] The simplest survey technique is a surface survey.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] It involves combing an area, usually on foot but sometimes using mechanized transport, to search for features or artifacts visible on the surface.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Surface survey cannot detect sites or features that are completely buried under earth or overgrown with vegetation.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Surface survey may also include mini-excavation techniques such as augers, corers, and shovel test pits.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] If no materials are found, the area surveyed is deemed sterile.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Aerial survey is conducted using cameras attached to airplanes, balloons, UAVs, or even Kites.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] A bird's-eye view is useful for quick mapping of large or complex sites.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Aerial photographs are used to document the status of the archaeological dig.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Aerial imaging can also detect many things not visible from the surface.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Plants growing above a buried human-made structure, such as a stone wall, will develop more slowly, while those above other types of features (such as middens) may develop more rapidly.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Photographs of ripening grain, which changes colour rapidly at maturation, have revealed buried structures with great precision.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Aerial photographs taken at different times of day will help show the outlines of structures by changes in shadows.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Aerial survey also employs ultraviolet, infrared, ground-penetrating radar wavelengths, Lidar and thermography.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Geophysical survey can be the most effective way to see beneath the ground.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Magnetometers detect minute deviations in the Earth's magnetic field caused by iron artifacts, kilns, some types of stone structures, and even ditches and middens.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Devices that measure the electrical resistivity of the soil are also widely used.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Archaeological features whose electrical resistivity contrasts with that of surrounding soils can be detected and mapped.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Some archaeological features (such as those composed of stone or brick) have higher resistivity than typical soils.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] In comparison, others (such as organic deposits or unfired clay) tend to have lower resistivity.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Although some archaeologists consider the use of metal detectors to be tantamount to treasure hunting, others deem them an effective tool in archaeological surveying.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Examples of formal archaeological use of metal detectors include musketball distribution analysis on English Civil War battlefields, metal distribution analysis before excavation of a 19th-century ship wreck, and service cable location during evaluation.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Metal detectorists have also contributed to archaeology, where they have made detailed records of their results and refrained from raising artifacts from their archaeological context.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] In the UK, metal detectorists have been invited to participate in the Portable Antiquities Scheme.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Regional survey in underwater archaeology uses geophysical or remote sensing devices such as a marine magnetometer, side-scan sonar, or sub-bottom sonar.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Archaeological excavation has existed even when the field was still the domain of amateurs, and it remains the primary source of data recovered in most field projects.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] It can reveal several types of information that are usually not accessible through surveys, such as stratigraphy, three-dimensional structure, and verifiably primary context.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Modern excavation techniques require that the precise locations of objects and features, known as their provenance or provenience, be recorded.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] This always involves determining their horizontal locations and, sometimes, their vertical positions as well (see also Primary Laws of Archaeology).
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Likewise, their association, or relationship with nearby objects and features, needs to be recorded for later analysis.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] This allows the archaeologist to deduce which artifacts and features were likely used together and which may be from different phases of activity.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] For example, excavation of a site reveals its stratigraphy; if a succession of distinct cultures occupied a site, artifacts from more recent cultures will lie above those from earlier ones.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Excavation is the most expensive phase of archaeological research, in relative terms.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Also, as a destructive process, it carries ethical concerns.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] As a result, very few sites are excavated in their entirety.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Again, the percentage of a site excavated depends greatly on the country and the "method statement" issued.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Sampling is even more important in excavation than in survey.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Sometimes large mechanical equipment, such as backhoes (JCBs), is used in excavation, especially to remove the topsoil (overburden), though this method is increasingly used with great caution.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Following this rather dramatic step, the exposed area is usually hand-cleaned with trowels or hoes to ensure that all features are apparent.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] The next task is to create a site plan and then use it to help determine the excavation method.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Features dug into the natural subsoil are normally excavated in portions to produce a visible archaeological section for recording.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] A feature, for example, a pit or a ditch, consists of two parts: the cut and the fill.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] The cut describes the edge of the feature where it meets the natural soil.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] The fill is what the feature is filled with, and will often appear quite distinct from the natural soil.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] The cut and fill are given consecutive numbers for recording purposes.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Scaled plans and sections of individual features are all drawn on site; black-and-white and colour photographs of them are taken; and recording sheets are filled in, describing the context of each feature.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] All this information serves as a permanent record of the now-destroyed archaeology and is used to describe and interpret the site.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Once artifacts and structures have been excavated or collected during surface surveys, they must be studied properly.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] This process is known as post-excavation analysis, and is usually the most time-consuming part of an archaeological investigation.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] It is not uncommon for final excavation reports for major sites to take years to be published.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] At a basic level of analysis, artifacts found are cleaned, catalogued and compared to published collections.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] This comparison process often involves classifying them typologically and identifying other sites with similar artifact assemblages.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] However, a much broader range of analytical techniques is available through archaeological science, allowing artifacts to be dated and their compositions examined.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Bones, plants, and pollen collected from a site can all be analysing using the methods of zooarchaeology, paleoethnobotany, palynology and stable isotopes while any texts can usually be deciphered.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] These techniques frequently provide information that would not otherwise be known, thereby contributing greatly to understanding a site.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] As with most academic disciplines, there are a very large number of archaeological sub-disciplines characterized by a specific method or type of material (e.g., lithic analysis, music, archaeobotany), geographical or chronological focus (e.g.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Near Eastern archaeology, Islamic archaeology, Medieval archaeology), other thematic concern (e.g. maritime archaeology, landscape archaeology, battlefield archaeology), or a specific archaeological culture or civilization (e.g.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Historical archaeology is the study of cultures with some form of writing and deals with objects and issues from the past.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] In medieval Europe, archaeologists have explored the illicit burial of unbaptized children in medieval texts and cemeteries.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] In downtown New York City, archaeologists have exhumed the 18th century remains of the African Burial Ground.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] When remnants of the WWII Siegfried Line were being destroyed, emergency archaeological digs were conducted whenever any part of the line was removed, to advance scientific knowledge and reveal details of its construction.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Ethnoarchaeology is the ethnographic study of living people, designed to aid in our interpretation of the archaeological record.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] The approach first gained prominence during the processual movement of the 1960s, and continues to be a vibrant component of post-processual and other current archaeological approaches.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Early ethnoarchaeological research focused on hunter-gatherer or foraging societies; today, ethnoarchaeological research encompasses a much wider range of human behaviour.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Experimental archaeology represents the application of the experimental method to develop more highly controlled observations of processes that create and impact the archaeological record.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] In the context of the logical positivism of processualism with its goals of improving the scientific rigor of archaeological epistemologies, the experimental method gained importance.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Experimental techniques remain a crucial component to improving the inferential frameworks for interpreting the archaeological record.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Archaeometry aims to systematize archaeological measurement.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] It emphasizes the application of analytical techniques from physics, chemistry, and engineering.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] It is a field of research that frequently focuses on determining the chemical composition of archaeological remains for source analysis.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Archaeometry also investigates different spatial characteristics of features, employing methods such as space syntax techniques and geodesy as well as computer-based tools such as geographic information system technology.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Rare earth elements patterns may also be used.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] A relatively nascent subfield is that of archaeological materials, designed to enhance understanding of prehistoric and non-industrial culture through scientific analysis of the structure and properties of materials associated with human activity.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Digital Archeology is an interdisciplinary field that applies information technology (IT), digital tools, and data management techniques to archaeology.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] It includes virtual archeology and computational archeology.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Examples of digital archaeology include the use of computer graphics to create virtual 3D models of sites, like the throne room of an Assyrian palace or ancient Rome.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Photogrammetry and digital topographical models are combined with astronomical calculations to check if structures, such as pillars, align with astronomical events like the sun's position at a solstice.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Agent-based modelling and simulation are used to understand past social dynamics and outcomes.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Data mining is applied to large collections of archaeological 'grey literature'.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Archaeology can be a subsidiary activity within Cultural resource management (CRM), also called Cultural heritage management (CHM) in the UK.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] CRM archaeologists frequently examine archaeological sites threatened by development.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] CRM accounts for most archaeological research done in the US and much of that in western Europe.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] In the US, CRM archaeology has been a growing concern since the passage of the National Historic Preservation Act (NHPA) of 1966.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Most scholars and politicians believe CRM has helped preserve much of the US's history and prehistory that would otherwise have been lost to the expansion of cities, dams, and highways.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Along with other statutes, the NHPA mandates that projects on federal land, or involving federal funds or permits, consider the effects of the project on each archaeological site.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] The application of CRM in the UK is not limited to government-funded projects.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Since 1990, PPG 16 has required planners to consider archaeology as a material consideration in determining applications for new development.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] As a result, archaeological organizations undertake mitigation work in advance of or during construction in archaeologically sensitive areas, at the developer's expense.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Some of the largest archaeological projects ever undertaken in the UK are due to major infrastructure projects such as the A14 road improvement scheme and the construction of HS2.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] In England, ultimate responsibility of care for the historic environment rests with the Department for Culture, Media and Sport in association with English Heritage.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] In Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland, the same responsibilities lie with Historic Scotland, Cadw and the Northern Ireland Environment Agency respectively.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] In France, the Institut national du patrimoine (The National Institute of Cultural Heritage) trains curators specialized in archaeology.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Their mission is to enhance the objects discovered.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] The curator is the link between scientific knowledge, administrative regulations, heritage objects, and the public.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Among the goals of CRM are the identification, preservation, and maintenance of cultural sites on public and private lands, and the removal of culturally valuable materials from areas where they would otherwise be destroyed by human activity, such as proposed construction.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] This study examines whether significant archaeological sites are present in the area affected by the proposed construction.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] If these do exist, time and money must be allotted for their excavation.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] If initial survey and/or test excavations indicate the presence of an extraordinarily valuable site, the construction may be prohibited entirely.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Cultural resources management has been criticized.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] CRM is conducted by private companies that bid for projects by submitting proposals outlining the work to be done and the expected budget.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] The agency responsible for the construction often chooses the proposal that asks for the least funding.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] CRM archaeologists face time pressure, often forced to complete their work in much less time than might be allotted to a purely academic project.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Compounding the time pressure is the vetting process for site reports that CRM firms are required to submit to the appropriate State Historic Preservation Office (SHPO).
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] From the SHPO's perspective, there is no difference between a report submitted by a CRM firm operating under a tight deadline and a multi-year academic project.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] The ratio of open academic archaeology positions to the number of archaeology MA/MSc and PhD students is low.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] CRM, once an intellectual backwater for individuals with "strong backs and weak minds", has attracted these graduates, and CRM offices are increasingly staffed by advance degreed workers with a track record of producing scholarly articles, but who also have extensive CRM field experience.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] The protection of archaeological finds for the public from catastrophes, wars, and armed conflicts is increasingly being implemented internationally.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] This happens, on the one hand, through international agreements and, on the other hand, through organizations that monitor or enforce protection.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] United Nations, UNESCO, and Blue Shield International deal with the protection of cultural heritage, including archaeological sites.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] This also applies to the integration of United Nations peacekeeping.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Blue Shield International has undertaken various fact-finding missions in recent years to protect archaeological sites during the wars in Libya, Syria, Egypt, and Lebanon.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] The importance of archaeological finds for identity, tourism, and sustainable economic growth is repeatedly emphasized internationally.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] The president of Blue Shield International, Karl von Habsburg, said during a cultural property protection mission in Lebanon in April 2019 with the United Nations Interim Force in Lebanon: "Cultural assets are part of the identity of the people who live in a certain place.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] If you destroy their culture, you also destroy their identity.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Early archaeology was largely an attempt to uncover spectacular artifacts and features or to explore vast, mysterious abandoned cities, and was mostly carried out by upper-class, scholarly men.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] This general tendency laid the foundation for the modern popular view of archaeology and archaeologists.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Many of the public view archaeology as something only available to a narrow demographic.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] The job of archaeologist is depicted as a "romantic adventurist occupation", and as a hobby more than a job in the scientific community.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Cinema audiences form a notion of "who archaeologists are, why they do what they do, and how relationships to the past are constituted", and are often under the impression that all archaeology takes place in a distant and foreign land, only to collect monetarily or spiritually priceless artifacts.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] The modern depiction of archaeology has distorted the public's perception of what it is.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Much thorough and productive research has indeed been conducted in dramatic locales such as Copán and the Valley of the Kings, but the bulk of modern archaeological activity and finds is not so sensational.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Archaeological adventure stories tend to ignore the painstaking work involved in carrying out modern surveys, excavations, and data processing.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Some archaeologists refer to such off-the-mark portrayals as "pseudoarchaeology".
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p01] Archaeologists are also highly reliant on public support; the question of for whom they work is often discussed.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Motivated by a desire to halt looting, curb pseudoarchaeology, and to help preserve archaeological sites through education and fostering public appreciation for the importance of archaeological heritage, archaeologists are mounting public-outreach campaigns.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] They seek to stop looting by combatting people who illegally take artifacts from protected sites, and by alerting people who live near archaeological sites of the threat of looting.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Common methods of public outreach include press releases, encouraging school field trips to sites under excavation led by professional archaeologists, and making reports and publications accessible outside academia.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Public appreciation of the significance of archaeology and archaeological sites often leads to improved protection from encroaching development or other threats.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] One audience for archaeologists' work is the public.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Archaeologists increasingly realize that their work can benefit audiences outside the field and academia, and that they have a responsibility to educate and inform the public about archaeology.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Local heritage awareness is aimed at increasing civic and individual pride through projects such as community excavation programs and better public presentations of archaeological sites and knowledge.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Department of Agriculture, Forest Service (USFS) operates a volunteer archaeology and historic preservation program called the Passport in Time (PIT).
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Volunteers work with professional USFS archaeologists and historians on national forests throughout the U.S.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Volunteers are involved in all aspects of professional archaeology under expert supervision.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Television programs, web videos, and social media can also bring an understanding of underwater archaeology to a broad audience.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] The *Mardi Gras* Shipwreck Project integrated a one-hour HD documentary, short videos for public viewing and video updates during the expedition as part of the educational outreach.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Webcasting is also another tool for educational outreach.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] For one week in 2000 and 2001, live underwater video of the *Queen Anne's Revenge* Shipwreck Project was webcast to the Internet as a part of the *QAR DiveLive* educational program that reached thousands of children around the world.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] The American Academy of Underwater Sciences.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Archived from the original on 19 February 2009.* Created and co-produced by Nautilus Productions and Marine Grafics, this project enabled students to talk to scientists and learn about methods and technologies used by the underwater archaeology team.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] In the UK, popular archaeology programs such as *Time Team* and *Meet the Ancestors* have resulted in a huge upsurge in public interest.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Where possible, archaeologists now make more provisions for public involvement and outreach in larger projects than they once did, and many local archaeological organizations operate within the Community archaeology framework to expand public involvement in smaller-scale, more local projects.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Archaeological excavation, however, is best undertaken by well-trained staff who can work quickly and accurately.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Often, this requires observing the necessary health and safety and indemnity insurance requirements when working on a modern building site with tight deadlines.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Certain charities and local government bodies sometimes offer places on research projects either as part of academic work or as a defined community project.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] There is also a flourishing industry selling places on commercial training excavations and archaeological holiday tours.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Archaeologists prize local knowledge and often liaise with local historical and archaeological societies, which is one reason community archaeology projects are becoming more common.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Often, archaeologists are assisted by the public in the locating of archaeological sites, which professional archaeologists have neither the funding nor the time to do.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Archaeological Legacy Institute (ALI), is a registered 501[c] [3] non-profit, media and education corporation registered in Oregon in 1999.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Pseudoarchaeology is an umbrella term for all activities that falsely claim to be archaeological but in fact violate commonly accepted and scientific archaeological practices.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] It includes much fictional archaeological work (discussed above), as well as some actual activity.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Many non-fiction authors have ignored the scientific methods of processual archaeology, or the specific critiques of it contained in post-processualism.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] An example of this type is the writing of Erich von Däniken.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] His 1968 book, *Chariots of the Gods?*, together with many subsequent lesser-known works, expounds a theory of ancient contacts between human civilization on Earth and more technologically advanced extraterrestrial civilizations.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] This theory, known as palaeocontact theory, or Ancient astronaut theory, is not exclusively Däniken's, nor did the idea originate with him.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Works of this nature are usually marked by the renunciation of well-established theories based on limited evidence and the interpretation of evidence with a preconceived theory in mind.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Looting of archaeological sites is an ancient problem.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] For instance, many of the tombs of the Egyptian pharaohs were looted during antiquity.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Archaeology stimulates interest in ancient objects, and people in search of artifacts or treasure cause damage to archaeological sites.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] The commercial and academic demand for artifacts contributes directly to the illicit antiquities trade.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Smuggling antiquities abroad to private collectors has caused great cultural and economic damage in many countries whose governments lack the resources and/or the will to deter it.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Looters damage and destroy archaeological sites, denying future generations information about their ethnic and cultural heritage.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Indigenous peoples especially lose access to and control over their 'cultural resources', ultimately denying them the opportunity to know their past.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Hodge the director of the Southwest Museum released a statement that the museum would no longer purchase or accept collections from looted contexts.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] The first conviction of the transport of artifacts illegally removed from private property under the Archaeological Resources Protection Act was in 1992 in the State of Indiana.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Archaeologists trying to protect artifacts may be placed in danger by looters or locals trying to protect the artifacts from archaeologists, who are viewed as looters by the locals.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Some historical archaeological sites are looted by metal detector hobbyists who search for artifacts using increasingly advanced technology.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Efforts are underway among all major Archaeological organizations to increase education and legitimate cooperation between amateurs and professionals in the metal detecting community.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] While most looting is deliberate, accidental looting can occur when amateurs, unaware of the importance of archaeological rigor, collect artifacts from sites and place them in private collections.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] In the United States, examples such as the case of Kennewick Man have illustrated the tensions between Native Americans and archaeologists, which can be summarized as a conflict between a need to remain respectful toward sacred burial sites and the academic benefit from studying them.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] For years, American archaeologists dug on Indian burial grounds and other places considered sacred, removing artifacts and human remains to storage facilities for further study.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] In some cases, human remains were not even thoroughly studied but instead archived rather than reburied.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Furthermore, Western archaeologists' views of the past often differ from those of tribal peoples.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] The West views time as linear; for many natives, it is cyclic.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] From a Western perspective, the past is long-gone; from a native perspective, disturbing the past can have dire consequences in the present.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] As a consequence, American Indians attempted to prevent the archaeological excavation of sites inhabited by their ancestors.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] At the same time, American archaeologists believed that the advancement of scientific knowledge justified continuing their studies.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] This contradictory situation was addressed by the Native American Graves Protection and Repatriation Act (NAGPRA, 1990), which sought to reach a compromise by limiting research institutions' right to possess human remains.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] In part due to the spirit of postprocessualism, some archaeologists have begun to actively enlist the assistance of indigenous peoples likely to be descended from those under study.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Archaeologists have also been obliged to re-examine what constitutes an archaeological site in light of what native peoples consider sacred space.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] To many native peoples, natural features such as lakes, mountains, or even individual trees have cultural significance.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Australian archaeologists have particularly explored this issue and attempted to survey these sites to help protect them from development.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Such work requires close links and trust between archaeologists and the people they are trying to help and, at the same time, study.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] While this cooperation presents a new set of challenges and hurdles to fieldwork, it has benefits for all parties involved.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Tribal elders cooperating with archaeologists can prevent the excavation of areas of sites that they consider sacred, while the archaeologists gain the elders' aid in interpreting their finds.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] There have also been active efforts to recruit Aboriginal peoples directly into the archaeological profession.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] A new trend in the heated controversy between First Nations groups and scientists is the repatriation of native artifacts to the original descendants.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] An example of this occurred on 21 June 2005, when community members and elders from a number of the 10 Algonquian nations in the Ottawa area convened on the Kitigan Zibi reservation near Maniwaki, Quebec, to inter ancestral human remains and burial goods—some dating back 6,000 years.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] It was not determined, however, if the remains were directly related to the Algonquin people who now inhabit the region.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] The remains may be of Iroquoian ancestry, since Iroquoian people inhabited the area before the Algonquin.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Moreover, the oldest of these remains might have no relation at all to the Algonquin or Iroquois and belong to an earlier culture that previously inhabited the area.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] The remains and artifacts, including jewelry, tools and weapons, were originally excavated from various sites in the Ottawa Valley, including Morrison and the Allumette Islands.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] They had been part of the Canadian Museum of Civilization's research collection for decades, some since the late 19th century.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Elders from various Algonquin communities conferred on an appropriate reburial, eventually deciding on traditional red cedar and birch bark boxes lined with red cedar chips, muskrat and beaver pelts.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] An inconspicuous rock mound marks the reburial site, where nearly 80 boxes of various sizes are buried.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Because of this reburial, no further scientific study is possible.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Although negotiations between the Kitigan Zibi community and the museum were at times tense, they reached an agreement.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] African Diaspora Archaeology is an area of study within the subfield of historical archaeology that studies those that have been forcibly transported through the Atlantic Slave Trade, the Trans-Saharan Slave Trade, and the Indian Ocean Slave Trade, as well as their descendants.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Although of global relevance, most research has been conducted in the Americas and Africa.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] In the 1990s, anthropologist Michael Blakey was the director of research during the New York African Burial Ground Project where he initiated a protocol for collaborating with the African descendant community.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] In 2011, the Society of Black Archaeologists was created in the United States.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Co-founders Ayana Omilade Flewellen, archaeologist at the University of California, Riverside and Justin Dunnavant, archaeologist and assistant professor of anthropology at the University of California, Los Angeles intend to build a restorative justice-based structure in archaeology.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] They suggest defining descendants not only in genealogical terms, but also to welcome input of African Americans whose ancestors had a shared historical experience in enslavement.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] The United States Senate unanimously passed a bill in December 2020 that centers African American cemeteries at risk in South Carolina.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] The bill is made to protect historic African burial grounds and can lead to the creation of an African American Burial Grounds Network.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Barbados, eight days after becoming a republic on November 30, 2021, announced plans for the construction of the *Newton Enslaved Burial Ground Memorial* as well as a museum dedicated to the history of the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] The Ghanaian-British architect David Adjaye is to lead the project that is to commemorate an estimated 570 West Africans buried in unmarked graves at the site of the former Newton sugar plantation.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Barbados can be seen as a good example of respectful preservation of an African burial ground.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Throughout the Americas however the burial grounds are in danger of being destroyed or human remains are being excavated without the descendant community being involved.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] In 2022, residents on Sint Eustatius, Dutch Caribbean spoke out strongly against what they found were unethical excavations of their ancestors on the Godet African Burial Ground and the Golden Rock African Burial Ground.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] These climate drivers will result in changes to flora and fauna and to ground conditions (both on and below the surface), thereby affecting archaeological deposits and structures; human responses to the climate crisis will also impact archaeological sites.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] The archaeologist's knowledge and skills are relevant to supporting society in adapting to a changing climate and a low-carbon future.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Another effect of higher temperatures has been the melting of glaciers and ice patches.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] This has led to the discovery of artifacts and bodies long buried in the ice, fostering the new field of glacial archaeology.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Archaeological sites can be seen as habitats that support ecosystems and fulfill biodiversity goals.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] As artificial intelligence (AI) continues to influence scientific research, its application in archaeological studies has become increasingly significant.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] For instance, AI models have been utilized to identify archaeological remains in the Empty Quarter of the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Additionally, AI technology has facilitated the discovery of 303 new geoglyphs in Nazca.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] AI is also useful in the translation of language and text, and can be used to help preserve cultural heritage.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Furthermore, with the help of LiDAR scanning, AI can also be used to create a 3D model of archaeological sites, such as in the Maya Lowlands where researchers are using these two technologies today.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] However, as the integration of AI in archaeology progresses, the risks in overuse of this become more apparent.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] The use of AI in archaeology creates a risk of oversimplification of data that is otherwise very complex.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] This oversimplification creates changes in how the data is interpreted, and creates concerns over the fostering of a deterministic view.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Another concern over AI is that it has the potential to perpetuate old and outdated ideas.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] As a tool AI will continue to grow in all scientific fields, with similar supportive and opposing arguments across all disciplines.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] While it can be used in some beneficial contexts, such as an instrument for translation, it also has the potential to do harm, such as the perpetuation of outdated ideas and the oversimplification of otherwise extremely complex data.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/archaeology-p02] Kansa has called for archaeologists to resist replacing human-curated, open scholarship with commercial AI summaries that prioritize engagement and plausibility over truth and ethical stewardship .
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/billy-griffiths-writer] Griffiths earned his Honours degree at the University of Sydney in 2011, basing his thesis on Gough Whitlam and Australia-China relations.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/billy-griffiths-writer] His father is Tom Griffiths, the W K Hancock Professor of History at the Australian National University.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/billy-griffiths-writer] In 2017 he earned his PhD at the University of Sydney, and was congratulated "on what his examiners agreed was a stunning PhD thesis".
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/billy-griffiths-writer] One examiner commented "Griffiths brilliantly charts the history of modern Aboriginal archaeology in Australia, and how the continent’s astonishing deep time history was discovered", and suggests that this could be "a landmark book".
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/billy-griffiths-writer] Griffiths was a research fellow at Deakin University from 2017 to 2019.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/billy-griffiths-writer] He wrote *The China Breakthrough: Whitlam in the Middle Kingdom, 1971* in 2012, based on the work he had done for his Honours thesis.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/billy-griffiths-writer] In the same year, he worked as the camp manager and cook for the team working on re-excavating Madjedbebe (formerly known as Malakunanja II), a sandstone rock shelter in Arnhem Land, in the Northern Territory, said to be the site of the oldest evidence of human habitation in the country.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/billy-griffiths-writer] At the dig, he met traditional owners, the Mirrar people, who have a deep connection to the site.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/billy-griffiths-writer] Upon returning from this expedition, he had so many things that he wanted to write about, which he sees as a way to process his thoughts: "I find writing hard; but not-writing is even harder".
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/billy-griffiths-writer] He wrote an article, "A world in a grain of sand: the Malakunanja II diaries", based on his experiences at the dig, in which he expanded on the theme of the "storied landscape" of Aboriginal history made evident by the site.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/billy-griffiths-writer] In 2015, he again spent time as cook at the dig.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/billy-griffiths-writer] He co-edited *The Archaeologist’s Book of Quotations*, published in 2015, with archaeologist Mike Smith of *The Australian* (also emeritus research fellow at the National Museum of Australia).
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/billy-griffiths-writer] In 2018, Griffiths published *Deep Time Dreaming: Uncovering Ancient Australia*, which, according to the publisher's blurb, "investigates a twin revolution: the reassertion of Aboriginal identity in the second half of the twentieth century, and the uncovering of the traces of ancient Australia".
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/billy-griffiths-writer] Described by one reviewer as a "readable, journalistic book about the history of Australian archaeology", the book won several awards and was nominated for several others (see below).
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/billy-griffiths-writer] As of April 2020, he is a lecturer in Cultural Heritage and Museum Studies at Deakin University, and Associate Investigator at the ARC Centre of Excellence for Australian Biodiversity and Heritage.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/billy-griffiths-writer] He is also a member of the Alfred Deakin Institute for Citizenship and Globalisation.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/billy-griffiths-writer] His research centres on cultural heritage, Indigenous history, political history, archaeology and seascapes.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/billy-griffiths-writer] In it, he describes the development of modern archaeology in Australia over about 60 years, including its involvement with Aboriginal political struggle.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/billy-griffiths-writer] Archaeology has contributed to a different understanding of Australian history and landscape.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/billy-griffiths-writer] According to the Australian Archaeological Association, the book helps to "introduce archaeological ideas, debates and methodologies to non-specialist audiences and to build bridges between the disciplines of history and archaeology, as John Mulvaney did throughout his life".
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/billy-griffiths-writer] The book also talks about the need of white Australians to learn of and come to terms with the magnitude of the dispossession of Aboriginal peoples of Australia, to help understand the need for Aboriginal reconciliation.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/billy-griffiths-writer] The work met with many favourable reviews by authors, in publications such as *The Monthly*, *The Sydney Morning Herald* and *Overland* literary journal.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Boston was founded on Shawmut Peninsula in 1630 by English Puritan settlers, who named the city after the market town of Boston, Lincolnshire, in England.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] During the American Revolution and Revolutionary War, Boston was home to several seminal events, including the Boston Massacre (1770), the Boston Tea Party (1773), Paul Revere's midnight ride (1775), the Battle of Bunker Hill (1775), and the Siege of Boston (1775–1776).
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Following American independence from Great Britain, Boston played an important national role as a port, manufacturing hub, and education and culture center, and the city expanded significantly beyond the original peninsula by filling in land and annexing neighboring towns.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Boston's many firsts include the nation's first public park (Boston Common, 1634), the first public school (Boston Latin School, 1635), and the first subway system (Tremont Street subway, 1897).
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Boston later emerged as a global leader in higher education and research and was the largest biotechnology hub in the world as of 2023.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The city is a national leader in scientific research, law, medicine, engineering, and business.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] With nearly 5,000 startup companies, the city is considered a global pioneer in innovation, entrepreneurship, and artificial intelligence.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Boston's economy is led by finance, professional and business services, information technology, and government.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The city's businesses and institutions rank among the top in the nation for environmental sustainability and new investment.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The name of the English town derives from its patron saint, St.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Botolph, in whose church Cotton served as the rector until he and Johnson emigrated to New England.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] In early sources, Lincolnshire's Boston was known as "St.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Botolph's town", which was later abbreviated as "Boston".
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Before this renaming, the settlement on the peninsula was known as "Shawmut" by William Blaxton and "Tremontaine" by the Puritan settlers he invited.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Before European colonization, the region surrounding present-day Boston was inhabited by the Massachusett people, who established small, seasonal communities in present-day Boston.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] In 1630, settlers led by John Winthrop arrived, and found Shawmut Peninsula nearly empty of Native people.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Most had died of European diseases borne by earlier settlers and traders.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Archaeological excavations have unearthed one of the oldest fishweirs in New England, located on Boylston Street, which Native people constructed as early as 7,000 years before European arrival in the Western Hemisphere.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The first European to live in what would become Boston was a University of Cambridge-educated Anglican cleric named William Blaxton.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] He was most directly responsible for the foundation of Boston by Puritan colonists in 1630, after Blaxton invited one of their leaders, Isaac Johnson, to cross Back Bay from the failing colony of Charlestown and share the peninsula with him.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] In September 1630 Puritans made the crossing to present-day Boston.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Puritan influence on Boston began even before the settlement was founded with the 1629 Cambridge Agreement, which created the Massachusetts Bay Colony and was signed by the colony's first governor, John Winthrop.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Puritan ethics and their focus on education also influenced the city's early history.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] In 1635, America's first public school, Boston Latin School, was founded in Boston.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Boston was the largest town in the Thirteen Colonies until Philadelphia outgrew it in the mid-18th century.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Boston's oceanfront location made it a lively port, and the town engaged in shipping and fishing during the colonial era.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Boston was a primary stop on the Caribbean trade route and imported large amounts of molasses, which led to the creation of Boston baked beans.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Boston's economy stagnated in the decades prior to the American Revolution.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] By the mid-18th century, New York City and Philadelphia both surpassed Boston in wealth.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] During this period, Boston encountered financial difficulties even as other New England cities were growing rapidly.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] , about the British army's decision to leave Boston, dated March 21, 1776.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Boston played a central role in the American Revolution.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Many crucial events of the American Revolution and subsequent American Revolutionary War occurred in or near Boston, where the city's revolutionary spirit against Britain's colonial governance was demonstrable and ultimately inspiring to the rest of the Thirteen Colonies.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] When the British Parliament passed the Stamp Act in 1765, the homes of Andrew Oliver, the official tasked with enforcing the Act, and Thomas Hutchinson, then lieutenant governor of Massachusetts Bay Colony, were raved by Boston mobs.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The British responded by sending two regiments to Boston in 1768 in an attempt to quell the revolt, but the increased British military presence in Boston only ended up further inflaming the Boston colonists.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] In 1770, during the Boston Massacre, British troops fired into a Boston mob that was protesting their presence.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The massacre forced the British to withdraw their troops and helped fuel revolutionary sentiment in the colonies.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] In May 1773, Parliament passed the Tea Act, which many colonists saw as a British attempt to compel them to accept taxes established by the Townshend Acts.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] This led to the Boston Tea Party, a defining event of the American Revolution in which angered Bostonians threw an entire shipment of tea sent from the East India Company into Boston Harbor, escalating the American Revolution.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The British monarchy responded furiously, implementing the Intolerable Acts and demanding compensation for the tea destroyed during the Boston Tea Party.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] This response, in turn, angered the colonists further, leading to the Battles of Lexington and Concord on April 19, 1775, the first battles of the American Revolutionary War, which were fought around Boston in Massachusetts Bay Colony.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] During the siege of Boston from April 19, 1775, to March 17, 1776, New England-based Patriot militia impeded movement by the British Army.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Sir William Howe, then commander-in-chief of British forces in North America, led the British army in the siege.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] On June 17, the British captured Charlestown in present-day Boston during the Battle of Bunker Hill during which the British Army outnumbered Patriot militia.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] But the British sustained irreplaceable casualties, turning the Battle of Bunker Hill into a pyrrhic victory for the British.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The Battle of Bunker Hill also demonstrated the skill and training of the Patriot militia, whose stubborn defense made it difficult for the British to capture Charlestown without suffering even further casualties.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] On June 14, 1775, in an effort to unify the Revolutionary War effort, the Second Continental Congress, convening in the colonial-era capital of Philadelphia, founded the Continental Army and unanimously appointed George Washington as its commander-in-chief.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Washington then immediately departed Philadelphia for Boston, where he arrived on July 2, 1775, and led the newly-formed Continental Army in the siege.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Fighting was limited to small-scale raids and skirmishes, and the Continental Army faced challenges with a deficiency of munitions and supplies.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Boston Neck, then narrow and only approximately 100 feet wide, impeded Washington's ability to invade Boston, which led to a prolonged stalemate between the Continental Army and British forces.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] A young officer, Rufus Putnam, came up with a plan to make portable fortifications out of wood, which were erected on the frozen ground under cover of darkness.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Putnam supervised the effort, which successfully installed the fortifications and dozens of cannons on Dorchester Heights that Henry Knox laboriously brought through the snow from Fort Ticonderoga.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The following morning, the astonished British Army awoke to see a large array of cannons bearing down on them.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] General Howe is believed to have said that the Americans had done more in one night than his British Army could have done in six months.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The British Army responded by attempting to launch a cannon barrage for two hours, but their shots could not reach the Continental Army's cannons at such a height.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The British then gave up, boarded their ships, and sailed away from Boston in what has come to be known as "Evacuation Day", which is now celebrated in Boston annually on March 17.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] After the British retreat, Washington was so impressed with the effort of Rufus Putnam that he appointed him as his chief engineer.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] After the Revolution, Boston's long seafaring tradition helped make it one of the nation's busiest ports for both domestic and international trade.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Boston's harbor activity was significantly curtailed by the Embargo Act of 1807, which was adopted during the Napoleonic Wars, and the War of 1812.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Foreign trade returned after these hostilities, but Boston's merchants had found alternatives for their capital investments in the meantime.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Manufacturing became an important component of the city's economy, and the city's industrial manufacturing overtook international trade in economic importance by the mid-19th century.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The small rivers bordering the city and connecting it to the surrounding region facilitated shipment of goods and led to a proliferation of mills and factories.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Later, a dense network of railroads furthered the region's industry and commerce.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] During this period, Boston also flourished culturally.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] It was admired for its rarefied literary life and generous artistic patronage.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Members of old Boston families, later dubbed "Boston Brahmins", came to be regarded as the nation's social and cultural elites.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] They are often associated with the American upper class, Harvard University, and the Episcopal Church.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Boston was a prominent port of the Atlantic slave trade in the New England Colonies, but was soon overtaken by Salem, Massachusetts, and Newport, Rhode Island.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Boston eventually became a center of the American abolitionist movement.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The city reacted largely negatively to the Fugitive Slave Act of 1850, contributing to President Franklin Pierce's attempt to make an example of Boston after Anthony Burns's attempt to escape to freedom.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] In 1822, the citizens of Boston voted to change the official name from the "Town of Boston" to the "City of Boston", and on March 19, 1822, the people of Boston accepted the charter incorporating the city.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] At the time Boston was chartered as a city, the population was about 46,226, while the area of the city was only 4.8 sq mi (12 km2).
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] In the 1820s, Boston's population grew rapidly, and the city's ethnic composition changed dramatically with the first wave of European immigrants.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Irish immigrants dominated the first wave of newcomers during this period, especially following the Great Famine; by 1850, about 35,000 Irish lived in Boston.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] In the latter half of the 19th century, the city saw increasing numbers of Irish, Germans, Lebanese, Syrians, French Canadians, and Russian and Polish Jews settling there.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] By the end of the 19th century, Boston's core neighborhoods had become enclaves of ethnically distinct immigrants with their residence yielding lasting cultural change.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Italians became the largest inhabitants of the North End, Irish dominated South Boston and Charlestown, and Russian Jews lived in the West End.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Irish and Italian immigrants brought with them Roman Catholicism.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Currently, Catholics make up Boston's largest religious community, and the Irish have played a major role in Boston politics since the early 20th century; prominent figures include the Kennedys, Tip O'Neill, and John F.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Between 1631 and 1890, the city tripled its area through land reclamation by filling in marshes, mud flats, and gaps between wharves along the waterfront.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Reclamation projects in the middle of the 19th century created significant parts of the South End, the West End, the Financial District, and Chinatown.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] After the Great Boston Fire of 1872, workers used building rubble as landfill along the downtown waterfront.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] During the mid-to-late 19th century, workers filled almost 600 acres (240 ha) of brackish Charles River marshlands west of Boston Common with gravel brought by rail from the hills of Needham Heights.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Other proposals were unsuccessful for the annexation of Brookline, Cambridge, and Chelsea.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Many architecturally significant buildings were built during the early years of the 20th century: Horticultural Hall, the Tennis and Racquet Club, Isabella Stewart Gardner Museum, Fenway Studios, Jordan Hall, and the Boston Opera House.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The Longfellow Bridge, built in 1906, was mentioned by Robert McCloskey in *Make Way for Ducklings*, describing its "salt and pepper shakers" feature.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Fenway Park, home of the Boston Red Sox, opened in 1912, with the Boston Garden opening in 1928.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Logan International Airport opened on September 8, 1923.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] On November 28, 1942, Boston's Cocoanut Grove nightclub was the site of the Cocoanut Grove fire, the deadliest nightclub fire in United States history, killing 492 people and injuring hundreds more.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] By the early- to mid-20th century, Boston declined economically as factories became old and obsolete and businesses moved out of the region for cheaper labor elsewhere.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Boston responded by initiating various urban renewal projects, under the direction of the Boston Redevelopment Authority (BRA) established in 1957.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] In 1958, BRA initiated a project to improve the historic West End neighborhood.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Extensive demolition was met with strong public opposition, and thousands of families were displaced.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The BRA continued implementing eminent domain projects, including the clearance of the vibrant Scollay Square area for construction of the modernist style Government Center.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] In 1965, the Columbia Point Health Center opened in the Dorchester neighborhood, the first Community Health Center in the United States.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] It mostly served the massive Columbia Point public housing complex adjoining it, which was built in 1953.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The health center is still in operation and was rededicated in 1990 as the Geiger-Gibson Community Health Center.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The Columbia Point complex itself was redeveloped and revitalized from 1984 to 1990 into a mixed-income residential development called Harbor Point Apartments.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] By the 1970s, the city's economy had begun to recover after 30 years of economic downturn.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] A large number of high-rises were constructed in the Financial District and in Boston's Back Bay during this period.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] This boom continued into the mid-1980s and resumed after a few pauses.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Hospitals such as Massachusetts General Hospital, Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center, and Brigham and Women's Hospital lead the nation in medical innovation and patient care.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Nevertheless, the city experienced conflict starting in 1974 over desegregation busing, which resulted in unrest and violence around public schools throughout the mid-1970s.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Boston has also experienced gentrification in the latter half of the 20th century, with housing prices increasing sharply since the 1990s when the city's rent control regime was struck down by statewide ballot proposition.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Boston is an intellectual, technological, and political center.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] However, it has lost some important regional institutions, including the loss to mergers and acquisitions of local financial institutions such as FleetBoston Financial, which was acquired by Charlotte-based Bank of America in 2004.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Boston-based department stores Jordan Marsh and Filene's have both merged into the New York City–based Macy's.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The 1993 acquisition of *The Boston Globe* by *The New York Times* was reversed in 2013 when it was resold to Boston businessman John W.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] In 2016, it was announced General Electric would be moving its corporate headquarters from Connecticut to the Seaport District in Boston, joining many other companies in this rapidly developing neighborhood.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The city also saw the completion of the Central Artery/Tunnel Project, known as the Big Dig, in 2007 after many delays and cost overruns.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] On April 15, 2013, two Chechen Islamist brothers detonated a pair of bombs near the finish line of the Boston Marathon, killing three people and injuring roughly 264.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The subsequent search for the bombers led to a lock-down of Boston and surrounding municipalities.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The region showed solidarity during this time as symbolized by the slogan *Boston Strong*.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] In 2016, Boston briefly shouldered a bid as the U.S. applicant for the 2024 Summer Olympics.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The bid was supported by the mayor and a coalition of business leaders and local philanthropists, but was eventually dropped due to public opposition.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The USOC then selected Los Angeles to be the American candidate with Los Angeles ultimately securing the right to host the 2028 Summer Olympics.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Nevertheless, Boston is one of eleven U.S. cities which will host matches during the 2026 FIFA World Cup, with games taking place at Gillette Stadium.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The city's elevation, as measured at Logan International Airport, is 19 ft (5.8 m) above sea level.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The highest point in Boston is Bellevue Hill at 330 ft (100 m) above sea level, and the lowest point is at sea level.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The city is adjacent to Boston Harbor, an arm of Massachusetts Bay, and by extension, the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Boston is surrounded by the Greater Boston metropolitan region.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The Charles River separates Boston's Allston-Brighton, Fenway-Kenmore and Back Bay neighborhoods from Watertown and Cambridge, and most of Boston from its own Charlestown neighborhood.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The Neponset River forms the boundary between Boston's southern neighborhoods and Quincy and Milton.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The Mystic River separates Charlestown from Chelsea and Everett, and Chelsea Creek and Boston Harbor separate East Boston from Downtown, the North End, and the Seaport.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Boston is sometimes called a "city of neighborhoods" because of the profusion of diverse subsections.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] More than two-thirds of inner Boston's modern land area did not exist when the city was founded.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Instead, it was created via the gradual filling in of the surrounding tidal areas over the centuries.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] This was accomplished using earth from the leveling or lowering of Boston's three original hills, the "Trimountain", after which Tremont Street is named, and with gravel brought by train from Needham to fill the Back Bay.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Back Bay is home to Christian Science Center, Copley Square, Newbury Street, and New England's two tallest buildings: the John Hancock Tower and the Prudential Center.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Near the John Hancock Tower is the old John Hancock Building with its prominent illuminated beacon, the color of which forecasts the weather.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Downtown and its immediate surroundings (including the Financial District, Government Center, and South Boston) consist largely of low-rise masonry buildings – often federal style and Greek revival – interspersed with modern high-rises.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Back Bay includes many prominent landmarks, such as the Boston Public Library, Trinity Church, single-family homes and wooden/brick multi-family row houses.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The South End Historic District is the largest surviving contiguous Victorian-era neighborhood in the US.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The geography of downtown and South Boston was particularly affected by the Central Artery/Tunnel Project (which ran from 1991 to 2007, and was known unofficially as the "Big Dig").
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] That project removed the elevated Central Artery and incorporated new green spaces and open areas.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Boston is located within the Boston Basin ecoregion, which is characterized by low and rolling hills with a number of ponds, lakes, and reservoirs.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Forests are mainly transition hardwoods such as oak-hickory mixed with white pine.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] As a coastal city built largely on fill, sea-level rise is of major concern to the city government.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] A climate action plan from 2019 anticipates 2 ft (1 m) to more than 7 ft (2 m) of sea-level rise in Boston by the end of the 21st century.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Many older buildings in certain areas of Boston are supported by wooden piles driven into the area's fill; these piles remain sound if submerged in water, but are subject to dry rot if exposed to air for long periods.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Groundwater levels have been dropping in many areas of the city, due in part to an increase in the amount of rainwater discharged directly into sewers rather than absorbed by the ground.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The Boston Groundwater Trust coordinates monitoring groundwater levels throughout the city via a network of public and private monitoring wells.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The city developed a climate action plan covering carbon reduction in buildings, transportation, and energy use.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The first such plan was commissioned in 2007, with updates released in 2011, 2014, and 2019.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] This plan includes the Building Energy Reporting and Disclosure Ordinance, which requires the city's larger buildings to disclose their yearly energy and water use statistics and to partake in an energy assessment every five years.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] A separate initiative, Resilient Boston Harbor, lays out neighborhood-specific recommendations for coastal resilience.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] In 2013, Mayor Thomas Menino introduced the Renew Boston Whole Building Incentive which reduces the cost of living in buildings that are deemed energy efficient.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Under the Köppen climate classification (using the −3 °C (27 °F) coldest month isotherm), Boston has ahumid subtropical climate (Köppen *Cfa*)..
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] If using the 0 °C (32 °F) coldest month isotherm, the city lies within the hot-summer humid continental zone (Köppen *Dfa*).
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Winters are cold and stormy, with occasional periods of heavy snow.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Spring and fall are usually cool and mild, with varying conditions dependent on wind direction and the position of the jet stream.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Prevailing wind patterns that blow offshore minimize the influence of the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] In winter, areas near the immediate coast often see more rain than snow, as warm air is sometimes drawn off the Atlantic.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Boston lies at the border between USDA plant hardiness zones 6b (away from the coastline) and 7a (close to the coastline).
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Receiving over 2,600 hours of sunshine annually, Boston is one of the sunniest oceanic cities located at its latitude globally.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The warmest month is July, with a mean temperature of 74.1 °F (23.4 °C).
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The coldest month is January, with a mean temperature of 29.9 °F (−1.2 °C).
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Periods exceeding 90 °F (32 °C) in summer and below freezing in winter are not uncommon but tend to be fairly short, with about 13 and 25 days per year seeing each, respectively.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Despite average winter temperatures near freezing, Boston can see entire winters without sustained periods of sub-freezing afternoons.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The winter of 2001-2002 recorded only two days entirely below freezing, with no day with a daily maximum temperature below 29 °F (−2 °C).
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The winter of 2023-2024 saw the yearly minimum temperature not falling below 14 °F (−10 °C) that winter.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Sub- 0 °F (−18 °C) readings usually occur every 3 to 5 years.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The most recent sub- 0 °F (−18 °C) reading occurred on February 4, 2023, when the temperature dipped down to −10 °F (−23 °C).
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] This was the lowest temperature reading in Boston since 1957.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Several decades may pass between 100 °F (38 °C) readings.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The last such reading occurred on June 24, 2025.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Boston's average window for freezing temperatures is November 9 to April 5.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Official temperature records have ranged from −18 °F (−28 °C) on February 9, 1934, up to 104 °F (40 °C) on July 4, 1911.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The record cold daily maximum is 2 °F (−17 °C) on December 30, 1917.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The record warm daily minimum is 83 °F (28 °C) on both August 2, 1975, and July 21, 2019.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The record high dew point is 79 °F (26 °C) recorded on August 10, 2001.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The most humid month on record is August 2018 with an average dewpoint of 66.8 °F (19.3 °C) for the month.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The hottest month on record is July 2019 with an average mean temperature of 78.7 °F (25.9 °C) for the month.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The month with the record warmest daily minimums was July 2019 with an average daily minimum of 70.7 °F (21.5 °C).
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Boston has recorded entire months in summer without nighttime lows below 63 °F (17 °C), the record most recently tied in August 2022 and previously set in July 2011 and July 2019.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Summer in Boston can also see entire months without dewpoints below 53 °F (12 °C), with the most recent occurrence being July 2008.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Boston has not recorded a summer since records began without at least one daily minimum of at least 69 °F (21 °C) or higher, and a dewpoint of 71 °F (22 °C) or greater.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The summers where the yearly maximum dew point topped out at 71 °F (22 °C) were in 1974 and 1982; and the yearly maximum daily minimum temperature at 69 °F (21 °C) in 1889.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The average yearly maximum daily minimum temperature is 76.9 °F (24.9 °C), and the average yearly maximum dew point is 75.4 °F (24.1 °C).
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Boston averages 43.6 in (1,110 mm) of precipitation a year, with 49.2 in (125 cm) of snowfall per season.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Most snowfall occurs from mid-November to early April.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] There is high year-to-year variability in snowfall.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] For instance, the winter of 2011–12 saw only 9.3 in (23.6 cm) of accumulating snow, but the previous winter, the corresponding figure was 81.0 in (206 cm).
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Boston's coastal location on the North Atlantic makes the city very prone to nor'easters, which can produce large amounts of snow and rain.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Fog is relatively common, particularly in spring and early summer.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Due to its coastal location, Boston often receives sea breezes, especially in the late spring, when water temperatures are still quite cold and temperatures at the coast can be more than 20 °F (11 °C) colder than a few miles inland, sometimes dropping by that amount near midday.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Thunderstorms typically occur from May to September.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Occasionally, they can become severe, with large hail, damaging winds, and heavy downpours.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Although downtown Boston has never been struck by a violent tornado, Boston has experienced many tornado warnings.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Damaging storms are more common to areas north, west, and northwest of the city.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Note: the US Census treats Hispanic/Latino as an ethnic category.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] This table excludes Latinos from the racial categories and assigns them to a separate category.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] In the 2020 census, Boston was estimated to have 691,531 residents living in 266,724 households—a 12% population increase over 2010.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Boston is the third-most densely populated large U.S. city of over half a million residents, and the most densely populated state capital.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Some 1.2 million persons may be within Boston's boundaries during work hours, and as many as 2 million during special events.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] This fluctuation of people is caused by hundreds of thousands of suburban residents who travel to the city for work, education, health care, and special events.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] For every 100 females, there were 92.0 males.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 89.9 males.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] There were 252,699 households, of which 20.4% had children under the age of 18 living in them, 25.5% were married couples living together, 16.3% had a female householder with no husband present, and 54.0% were non-families.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] 37.1% of all households were made up of individuals, and 9.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The average household size was 2.26 and the average family size was 3.08.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] In 2024, the median household income in Boston was $97,791, while the median income for a family was $110,710.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] In 2011, full-time year-round male workers had a median income of $52,544 versus $46,540 for full-time year-round female workers.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The per capita income for the city was $33,158.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] 21.4% of the population and 16.0% of families were below the poverty line.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Of the total population, 28.8% of those under the age of 18 and 20.4% of those 65 and older were living below the poverty line.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Boston has a significant racial wealth gap with White Bostonians having a median net worth of $247,500 compared to an $8 median net worth for non-immigrant Black residents and $0 for Dominican immigrant residents.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] From the 1950s to the end of the 20th century, the proportion of non-Hispanic Whites in Boston declined.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] In 2000, non-Hispanic Whites were 49.5% of Boston's population, making the city majority minority for the first time.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] In the 21st century, Boston has experienced significant gentrification, during which affluent Whites have moved into formerly non-White areas.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Census Bureau estimated non-Hispanic Whites again formed a slight majority.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] By 2010, in part due to a crash in housing prices, as well as increased efforts to make affordable housing more available, the non-White population had rebounded and non-Hispanic White residents formed 47% of the population.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] constitute the largest ethnicity in Boston.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] In 2011, African-Americans comprised 22% of the city's population.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] People of Irish descent formed the second-largest single ethnic group in the city, making up 15.8% of the population, followed by Italians, accounting for 8.3% of the population.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] People of West Indian and Caribbean ancestry are another sizable group, collectively at over 15%.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] In Greater Boston, these numbers grew significantly, with 150,000 Dominicans according to 2018 estimates, 134,000 Puerto Ricans, 57,500 Salvadorans, 39,000 Guatemalans, 36,000 Mexicans, and over 35,000 Colombians.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] East Boston has a diverse Hispanic/Latino population of Salvadorans, Colombians, Guatemalans, Mexicans, Dominicans and Puerto Ricans.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Hispanic populations in southwest Boston neighborhoods are mainly made up of Dominicans and Puerto Ricans, usually sharing neighborhoods in this section with African Americans and Blacks with origins from the Caribbean and Africa especially Cape Verdeans and Haitians.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Neighborhoods such as Jamaica Plain and Roslindale have a growing number of Dominican Americans.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] There is a large and historical Armenian community in Boston, and the city is home to the Armenian Heritage Park.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Over 27,000 Chinese Americans made their home in Boston city proper in 2013.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] Data is from the American Community Survey's five-year estimates 2008–2012.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] In a 2023-24 study by the Pew Research Center, 47% of the population of the city identified themselves as Christians, with 21% attending a variety of Protestant churches and 24% professing Roman Catholic beliefs.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The remaining 13% are composed of adherents of Judaism, Buddhism, Islam, Hinduism, and other faiths.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] In 2010, the Catholic Church had the highest number of adherents as a single denomination in the Greater Boston area, with more than two million members and 339 churches, followed by the Episcopal Church with 58,000 adherents in 160 churches.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] The United Church of Christ had 55,000 members and 213 churches.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] In 2015, the Boston metro area had a Jewish population of approximately 248,000.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] More than half the Jewish households in the Greater Boston area reside in the city itself, Brookline, Newton, Cambridge, Somerville, or adjacent towns.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p01] A small minority practices Confucianism, and some practice Boston Confucianism, an American evolution of Confucianism adapted for Boston intellectuals.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] A global city, Boston is ranked among the top 30 most economically powerful cities in the world.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Encompassing $610 billion, the Greater Boston metropolitan area has the eighth-largest economy in the country and 16th-largest in the world.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston's colleges and universities exert a significant impact on the regional economy.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston attracts more than 350,000 college students from around the world, who contribute more than US$4.8 billion annually to the city's economy.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The area's schools are major employers and attract industries to the city and surrounding region.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The city is home to a number of technology companies and is a hub for biotechnology, with the Milken Institute rating Boston as the top life sciences cluster in the country.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston receives the highest absolute amount of annual funding from the National Institutes of Health of all cities in the United States.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston is considered highly innovative for a variety of reasons, including the presence of academia, access to venture capital, and the presence of many high-tech companies.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The Route 128 corridor and Greater Boston continue to be a major center for venture capital investment, and high technology remains an important sector.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Tourism composes a large part of Boston's economy, with 21.2 million domestic and international visitors spending $8.3 billion in 2011.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Excluding visitors from Canada and Mexico, over 1.4 million international tourists visited Boston in 2014, with those from China and the United Kingdom leading the list.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston's status as a state capital as well as the regional home of federal agencies has rendered law and government to be another major component of the city's economy.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston is a major seaport along the East Coast of the United States and the oldest continuously operated industrial and fishing port in the Western Hemisphere.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] In the 2018 Global Financial Centres Index, Boston was ranked as having the 13th-most competitive financial services center in the world and the second-most competitive in the United States.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston-based Fidelity Investments helped popularize the mutual fund in the 1980s and has made Boston one of the top financial centers in the United States and a center for venture capital firms.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston is home to the headquarters of Santander Bank and State Street Corporation, the latter specializing in asset management and custody services.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston is a printing and publishing center—Houghton Mifflin Harcourt is headquartered within the city, along with Bedford-St.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Pearson PLC publishing units employ several hundred people in Boston.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston is home to two convention centers—the Hynes Convention Center in the Back Bay and the Boston Convention and Exhibition Center on the South Boston waterfront.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston is home to the headquarters of several major athletic and footwear companies including Converse, New Balance, and Reebok.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Rockport, Puma and Wolverine World Wide, Inc. headquarters or regional offices are just outside the city.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston Public Schools enroll 57,000 students attending 145 schools, including Boston Latin Academy, John D.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] O'Bryant School of Math & Science, and the Boston Latin School.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The Boston Latin School was established in 1635 and is the oldest public high school in the US.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston also operates the United States' second-oldest public high school and its oldest public elementary school.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The system's students are 40% Hispanic or Latino, 35% Black or African American, 13% White, and 9% Asian.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] There are private, parochial, and charter schools.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Approximately 3,300 minority students attend participating suburban schools through the Metropolitan Educational Opportunity Council.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] In September 2019, the city began Boston Saves, a program that provides every child enrolled in the city's kindergarten system a savings account, containing $50 to be used toward college or career training.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Several of the highest-ranked universities in the world are near Boston.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Three universities with a major presence in the city, Harvard, MIT, and Tufts, are just outside of Boston in the cities of Cambridge and Somerville, known as the *Brainpower Triangle*.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Harvard is the nation's oldest institute of higher education and is centered across the Charles River in Cambridge, though the majority of its land holdings and a substantial amount of its educational activities are in Boston.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Its business school and athletics facilities are in Boston's Allston neighborhood, and its medical, dental, and public health schools are located in the Longwood area.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) originated in Boston and was long known as "Boston Tech"; it moved across the river to Cambridge in 1916.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Tufts University's main campus is north of the city in Somerville and Medford, though its medical and dental schools are located in Boston's Chinatown at Tufts Medical Center.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Greater Boston has more than 50 colleges and universities, with 250,000 students enrolled in Boston and Cambridge alone.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston's only public university is the University of Massachusetts Boston on Columbia Point in Dorchester.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Roxbury Community College and Bunker Hill Community College are the city's two public community colleges.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Altogether, Boston's colleges and universities employ more than 42,600 people, accounting for nearly seven percent of the city's workforce.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Five members of the Association of American Universities are in Greater Boston, more than any other metropolitan area: Harvard University, the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Tufts University, Boston University, and Brandeis University.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Greater Boston contains seven Highest Research Activity (R1) Universities as per the Carnegie Classification.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] This includes, in addition to the aforementioned five, Boston College, and Northeastern University.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] This is, by a large margin, the highest concentration of such institutions in a single metropolitan area.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Hospitals, universities, and research institutions in Greater Boston received more than $1.77 billion in National Institutes of Health grants in 2013, more money than any other American metropolitan area.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] This high density of research institutes also contributes to Boston's high density of early career researchers, which, due to high housing costs in the region, have been shown to face housing stress.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The region is home to several conservatories and art schools, including the New England Conservatory (the oldest independent conservatory in the United States), the Boston Conservatory, and Berklee College of Music, which has made Boston an important city for jazz music.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Many trade schools also exist in the city such as the Boston Career Institute, the North Bennet Street School, and Greater Boston Joint Apprentice Training Center.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston has a strong mayor–council government system in which the mayor, elected every fourth year, has extensive executive power.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Michelle Wu became mayor in November 2021, succeeding Kim Janey who became the Acting Mayor in March 2021 following Marty Walsh's confirmation to the position of Secretary of Labor in the Biden/Harris Administration.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Walsh's predecessor Thomas Menino's twenty-year tenure was the longest in Boston's history.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The Boston City Council is elected every two years.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] There are nine district seats, and four citywide "at-large" seats.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The School Committee, which oversees the Boston Public Schools, is appointed by the mayor.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston uses an algorithm called CityScore to measure the effectiveness of city services.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] This score is available on a public online dashboard and allows city managers in police, fire, schools, emergency management services, and 3-1-1 to take action and make adjustments in areas of concern.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] As the capital of Massachusetts, Boston plays a major role in state politics.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston has several federal facilities, including the John F.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Kennedy Federal Office Building, the Thomas P.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] McCormack Post Office and Courthouse, and the Federal Reserve Bank of Boston.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The United States Court of Appeals for the First Circuit and the United States District Court for the District of Massachusetts are housed in The John Joseph Moakley United States Courthouse.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Federally, Boston is split between two congressional districts.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Three-fourths of Boston is in the 7th district and is represented by Ayanna Pressley.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The remaining southern fourth is in the 8th district and is represented by Stephen Lynch.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Both are Democrats; a Republican has not represented a significant portion of Boston in over a century.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The state's senior member of the United States Senate is Democrat Elizabeth Warren, first elected in 2012.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The state's junior member of the United States Senate is Democrat Ed Markey, who was elected in 2013 to succeed John Kerry after Kerry's appointment and confirmation as the United States Secretary of State.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston included $414 million in spending on the Boston Police Department in the fiscal 2021 budget.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] This is the second largest allocation of funding by the city after the allocation to Boston Public Schools.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Like many major American cities, Boston has experienced a great reduction in violent crime since the early 1990s.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston's low crime rate since the 1990s has been credited to the Boston Police Department's collaboration with neighborhood groups and church parishes to prevent youths from joining gangs, as well as involvement from the United States Attorney and District Attorney's offices.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] This helped lead in part to what has been touted as the "Boston Miracle".
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Murders in Boston dropped from 152 in 1990, a murder rate of 26.5 per 100,000 people, to 31—not one of them a juvenile—in 1999, for a murder rate of 5.26 per 100,000.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] According to the Uniform Crime Reporting (UCR) program in 2022, Boston had 3,955 reported violent crimes, which include homicide, rape, robbery, and aggravated assault, and 11,514 reported property crimes, which include arson, burglary, larceny-theft, and motor vehicle theft.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] With a violent crime rate of 608.7 per 100,000 people, the city's violent crime rate is higher than Massachusetts' rate of 322 per 100,000 people and the national rate of 380.7 per 100,000 people.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] While Boston's property crime rate, at 1,772.0 per 100,000 people, is higher than Massachusetts' property crime rate of 1,070.1 per 100,000 people, it is lower than the national property crime rate of 1,954.4 per 100,000 people.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston shares many cultural roots with greater New England, including a dialect of the non-rhotic Eastern New England accent known as the Boston accent and a regional cuisine with a large emphasis on seafood, salt, and dairy products.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston also has its own collection of neologisms known as *Boston slang* and sardonic humor.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] In the early 1800s, William Tudor wrote that Boston was "'perhaps the most perfect and certainly the best-regulated democracy that ever existed.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] In the 19th century, Ralph Waldo Emerson, Henry David Thoreau, Nathaniel Hawthorne, Margaret Fuller, James Russell Lowell, and Henry Wadsworth Longfellow wrote in Boston.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Some consider the Old Corner Bookstore to be the "cradle of American literature", the place where these writers met and where *The Atlantic Monthly* was first published.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] In 1852, the Boston Public Library was founded as the first free library in the United States.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston's literary culture continues today thanks to the city's many universities and the Boston Book Festival.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Music is afforded a high degree of civic support in Boston.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The Boston Symphony Orchestra is one of the "Big Five", a group of the greatest American orchestras, and the classical music magazine *Gramophone* called it one of the "world's best" orchestras.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Symphony Hall (west of Back Bay) is home to the Boston Symphony Orchestra and the related Boston Youth Symphony Orchestra, which is the largest youth orchestra in the nation, and to the Boston Pops Orchestra.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Other concerts are held at the New England Conservatory's Jordan Hall.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The Boston Ballet performs at the Boston Opera House.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Other performing-arts organizations in the city include the Boston Lyric Opera Company, Opera Boston, Boston Baroque (the first permanent Baroque orchestra in the US), and the Handel and Haydn Society (one of the oldest choral companies in the United States).
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston is a center for contemporary classical music with a number of performing groups, several of which are associated with the city's conservatories and universities.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] These include the Boston Modern Orchestra Project and Boston Musica Viva.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Several theaters are in or near the Theater District south of Boston Common, including the Cutler Majestic Theatre, Citi Performing Arts Center, the Colonial Theater, and the Orpheum Theatre.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The city is the site of several events during the Fourth of July period.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] They include the week-long Harborfest festivities and a Boston Pops concert accompanied by fireworks on the banks of the Charles River.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Several historic sites relating to the American Revolution period are preserved as part of the Boston National Historical Park because of the city's prominent role.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Many are found along the Freedom Trail, which is marked by a red line of bricks embedded in the ground.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The city is home to several art museums and galleries, including the Museum of Fine Arts and Isabella Stewart Gardner Museum.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The Institute of Contemporary Art is housed in a contemporary building designed by Diller Scofidio + Renfro in the Seaport District.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston's South End Art and Design District (SoWa) and Newbury St. are both art gallery destinations.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Columbia Point is the location of the University of Massachusetts Boston, the Edward M.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Kennedy Institute for the United States Senate, the John F.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Kennedy Presidential Library and Museum, and the Massachusetts Archives and Commonwealth Museum.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The Boston Athenæum (one of the oldest independent libraries in the United States), Boston Children's Museum, Bull & Finch Pub (whose building is known from the television show *Cheers*), Museum of Science, and the New England Aquarium are within the city.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston has been a noted religious center from its earliest days.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Boston serves nearly 300 parishes and is based in the Cathedral of the Holy Cross (1875) in the South End, while the Episcopal Diocese of Massachusetts serves just under 200 congregations, with the Cathedral Church of St.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Unitarian Universalism has its headquarters in the Fort Point neighborhood.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The Christian Scientists are headquartered in Back Bay at the Mother Church (1894).
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The oldest church in Boston is First Church in Boston, founded in 1630.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] King's Chapel was the city's first Anglican church, founded in 1686 and converted to Unitarianism in 1785.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Other churches include Old South Church (1669), Christ Church (better known as Old North Church, 1723), the oldest church building in the city, Trinity Church (1733), Park Street Church (1809), and Basilica and Shrine of Our Lady of Perpetual Help on Mission Hill (1878).
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston has teams in the four major North American men's professional sports leagues plus Major League Soccer.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] As of 2024, the city has won 40 championships in these leagues.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The Boston Red Sox, a founding member of the American League of Major League Baseball in 1901, play their home games at Fenway Park, near Kenmore Square, in the city's Fenway section.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Built in 1912, it is the oldest sports arena or stadium in active use in the United States among the four major professional American sports leagues, Major League Baseball, the National Football League, National Basketball Association, and the National Hockey League.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston was the site of the first game of the first modern World Series, in 1903.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The series was played between the AL Champion Boston Americans and the NL champion Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Persistent reports that the team was known in 1903 as the "Boston Pilgrims" appear to be unfounded.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston's first professional baseball team was the Red Stockings, one of the charter members of the National Association in 1871, and of the National League in 1876.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The team played under that name until 1883, under the name Beaneaters until 1911, and under the name Braves from 1912 until they moved to Milwaukee after the 1952 season.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Since 1966 they have played in Atlanta as the Atlanta Braves.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] TD Garden, formerly called the FleetCenter and built to replace the since-demolished Boston Garden, is above North Station and is the home of two major league teams: the Boston Bruins of the National Hockey League and the Boston Celtics of the National Basketball Association.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The Bruins were the first American member of the National Hockey League and an Original Six franchise.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The Boston Celtics were founding members of the Basketball Association of America, one of the two leagues that merged to form the NBA.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The Celtics have won eighteen championships, the most of any NBA team.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] While they have played in suburban Foxborough since 1971, the New England Patriots of the National Football League were founded in 1960 as the Boston Patriots, changing their name after relocating.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] They share Gillette Stadium with the New England Revolution of Major League Soccer.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Another team associated with Boston who plays outside the city is the Boston Fleet of the PWHL, which plays at the Tsongas Center in nearby Lowell.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] During the inaugural 2024 PWHL playoffs, the Fleet (then simply known as PWHL Boston) made it to the Walter Cup finals, where they lost to the Minnesota Frost (PWHL Minnesota at the time).
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The area's many colleges and universities are active in college athletics.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Four NCAA Division I members play in the area—Boston College, Boston University, Harvard University, and Northeastern University.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Of the four, only Boston College participates in college football at the highest level, the Football Bowl Subdivision.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Harvard participates in the second-highest level, the Football Championship Subdivision.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] These four universities participate in the Beanpot, an annual men's and women's ice hockey tournament.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The men's Beanpot is hosted at the TD Garden, while the women's Beanpot is held at each member school's home arena on a rotating basis.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston has Esports teams, such as the Overwatch League (OWL)'s Boston Uprising.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Established in 2017, they were the first team to complete a perfect stage with 0 losses.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The Boston Breach is another esports team in the Call of Duty League (CDL).
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] One of the best-known sporting events in the city is the Boston Marathon, the 26.2 mi (42.2 km) race which is the world's oldest annual marathon, run on Patriots' Day in April.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The Red Sox traditionally play a home game starting around 11 a.m. on the same day, with the early start time allowing fans to watch runners finish the race nearby after the conclusion of the ballgame.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Another major annual event is the Head of the Charles Regatta, held in October.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston Common, near the Financial District and Beacon Hill, is the oldest public park in the United States.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Along with the adjacent Boston Public Garden, it is part of the Emerald Necklace, a string of parks designed by Frederick Law Olmsted to run through the city.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The Emerald Necklace includes the Back Bay Fens, Arnold Arboretum, Jamaica Pond, Boston's largest body of freshwater, and Franklin Park, the city's largest park and home of the Franklin Park Zoo.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Another major park is the Esplanade, along the banks of the Charles River.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The Hatch Shell, an outdoor concert venue, is adjacent to the Charles River Esplanade.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Other parks are scattered throughout the city, with major parks and beaches near Castle Island and the south end, in Charlestown and along the Dorchester, South Boston, and East Boston shorelines.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston's black community is served by the *Bay State Banner*, a newspaper focused on the issues of interest to black Bostonians.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The *Bay State Banner* has operated since 1965.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The city's growing Latino population has given rise to a number of local and regional Spanish-language newspapers.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] These include *El Planeta* (owned by the former publisher of the *Boston Phoenix*), *El Mundo*, and *La Semana*.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] *Siglo21*, with its main offices in nearby Lawrence, is also widely distributed.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] LGBT publications serve Boston's large LGBT (lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender) population such as *The Rainbow Times*, the only minority and lesbian-owned LGBT news magazine.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Founded in 2006, *The Rainbow Times* is now based out of Boston, but serves all of New England.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston is the largest broadcasting market in New England, with the radio market being the ninth largest in the United States.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Several major AM stations include talk radio WRKO, sports/talk station WEEI, and news radio WBZ (AM).
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] WBZ is a 50,000 watt "clear channel" station whose nighttime broadcasts are heard hundreds of miles from Boston.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] A variety of commercial FM radio formats serve the area, as do NPR stations WBUR and WGBH.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] College and university radio stations include WERS (Emerson), WHRB (Harvard), WUMB (UMass Boston), WMBR (MIT), WZBC (Boston College), WMFO (Tufts University), WBRS (Brandeis University), WRBB (Northeastern University) and WMLN-FM (Curry College).
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The Boston television DMA, which also includes Manchester, New Hampshire, is the eighth largest in the United States.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The city is also home to PBS member station WGBH-TV 2, a major producer of PBS programs, which also operates WGBX 44.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Spanish-language television networks, including UniMás (WUTF-TV 27), Telemundo (WNEU 60, a sister station to WBTS-CD), and Univisión (WUNI 66), have a presence in the region, with WNEU and WUNI serving as network owned-and-operated stations.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Most of the area's television stations have their transmitters in nearby Needham and Newton along the Route 128 corridor.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Seven Boston television stations are carried by satellite television and cable television providers in Canada.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Many of Boston's medical facilities are associated with universities.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The Longwood Medical and Academic Area, adjacent to the Fenway, district, is home to a large number of medical and research facilities, including Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center, Brigham and Women's Hospital, Boston Children's Hospital, Dana–Farber Cancer Institute, and Joslin Diabetes Center.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Prominent medical facilities, including Massachusetts General Hospital, Massachusetts Eye and Ear Infirmary and Spaulding Rehabilitation Hospital are in the Beacon Hill area.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Many of the facilities in Longwood and near Massachusetts General Hospital are affiliated with Harvard Medical School.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Tufts Medical Center (formerly Tufts-New England Medical Center), in the southern portion of the Chinatown neighborhood, is affiliated with Tufts University School of Medicine.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston Medical Center, in the South End neighborhood, is the region's largest safety-net hospital and trauma center.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Formed by the merger of Boston City Hospital, the first municipal hospital in the United States, and Boston University Hospital, Boston Medical Center now serves as the primary teaching facility for the Boston University School of Medicine.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston Medical Center – Brighton (formerly St.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Elizabeth's Medical Center) is located in the Brighton neighborhood.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] New England Baptist Hospital is in Mission Hill.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The city has Veterans Affairs medical centers in the Jamaica Plain and West Roxbury neighborhoods.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Logan International Airport, in East Boston and operated by the Massachusetts Port Authority (Massport), is Boston's principal airport.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Nearby general aviation airports are Beverly Regional Airport and Lawrence Municipal Airport to the north, Hanscom Field to the west, and Norwood Memorial Airport to the south.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Massport also operates several major facilities within the Port of Boston, including a cruise ship terminal and facilities to handle bulk and container cargo in South Boston, and other facilities in Charlestown and East Boston.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Downtown Boston's streets grew organically, so they do not form a planned grid, unlike those in later-developed Back Bay, East Boston, the South End, and South Boston.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston is the eastern terminus of I-90, which in Massachusetts runs along the Massachusetts Turnpike.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The Central Artery follows I-93 as the primary north–south artery that carries most of the through traffic in Downtown Boston.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Other major highways include US 1, which carries traffic to the North Shore and areas south of Boston, US 3, which connects to the northwestern suburbs, MA 3, which connects to the South Shore and Cape Cod, and MA 2 which connects to the western suburbs.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Surrounding the city is MA 128, a partial beltway which has been largely subsumed by other routes (mostly I-95 and I-93).
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] With nearly a third of Bostonians using public transit for their commute to work, Boston has the sixth-highest rate of public transit usage in the country.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The city of Boston has a higher than average percentage of households without a car.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] In 2016, 33.8 percent of Boston households lacked a car, compared with the national average of 8.7 percent.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The city averaged 0.94 cars per household in 2016, compared to a national average of 1.8.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston's public transportation agency, the Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority (MBTA), operates the oldest underground rapid transit system in the Americas and is the fourth-busiest rapid transit system in the country, with 65.5 mi (105 km) of track on four lines.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The MBTA also operates busy bus, commuter rail, and ferry networks.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Amtrak intercity rail to Boston is provided through four stations: South Station, North Station, Back Bay, and Route 128.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] South Station is a major intermodal transportation hub and is the terminus of Amtrak's *Northeast Regional*, *Acela Express*, and *Lake Shore Limited* routes, in addition to multiple MBTA services.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Back Bay is also served by MBTA and those three Amtrak routes, while Route 128, in the southwestern suburbs of Boston, is only served by the *Acela Express* and *Northeast Regional*.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Meanwhile, Amtrak's *Downeaster* to Brunswick, Maine terminates in North Station, and is the only Amtrak route to do so.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Nicknamed "The Walking City", Boston hosts more pedestrian commuters than do other comparably populated cities.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Owing to factors such as necessity, the compactness of the city and large student population, 13 percent of the population commutes by foot, making it the highest percentage of pedestrian commuters in the country out of the major American cities.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] As of 2024, Walk Score ranks Boston as the third most walkable U.S. city, with a Walk Score of 83, a Transit Score of 72, and a Bike Score of 69.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] Boston has one of the highest rates of bicycle commuting.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The bikeshare program Bluebikes, originally called Hubway, launched in late July 2011.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] The system has 480 stations with a total of 4,500 bikes.
[src:archaeological-institute-of-america/boston-p02] PBSC Urban Solutions provides bicycles and technology for this bike-sharing system.
